{{Canadian politics}}

This is a '''list of Canadian ministries''', the collective body of [[ministers of the Crown]] that [[advice (constitutional)|advises]] the [[Monarchy of Canada|Canadian monarch]]—presently Queen [[Elizabeth II]]—on how to exercise their [[Crown prerogative]]s. Since [[Canadian Confederation]], July 1, 1867, there have been 29 [[Ministry (collective executive)|ministries]].

In Canada, a ministry is formed when a new [[Prime Minister of Canada|prime minister]] is appointed and dissolved when that individual leaves office. The one exception occurred in 1917, when [[incumbent]] Prime Minister Sir [[Robert Borden]] formed a new [[national unity government]] (the [[10th Canadian Ministry]]) as a [[World War I|wartime]] [[coalition government|coalition]] composed primarily of members of his own [[Conservative Party of Canada (historical)|Conservative Party]] with some individual [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]] [[Member of Parliament|members of parliament]].

In contrast to various other [[Commonwealth realm]]s (such as [[Australia]] and the [[United Kingdom]]) where a "new" ministry is considered to have been formed after every [[general election]] regardless of the winner, [[elections in Canada]] do not cause dissolution of the ministry unless they result in the government's defeat. As such, the current [[29th Canadian Ministry|29th Ministry]], chaired by Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]], began governing shortly before the opening of the [[42nd Parliament of Canada|42nd Parliament]] in 2015.

With a duration of 15 years, 87 days, the [[8th Canadian Ministry|8th Ministry]], under the leadersip of Sir [[Wilfrid Laurier]], was the lengthiest; the 68-day-long [[7th Canadian Ministry|7th Ministry]], under the leadership of Sir [[Charles Tupper]], was the briefest. [[William Lyon Mackenzie King]] led three ministries—the [[12th Canadian Ministry|12th]], [[14th Canadian Ministry|14th]], and [[16th Canadian Ministry|16th]]—the most for any Canadian prime minister.

